</p>
<p>When we try to run this, we get an <em>exception</em>:</p>
<blockquote><p>Base table or view not found</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The error is coming from <code>PdoShipStorage</code> on line 18, but we can also see the line
that called this: <code>ShipLoader</code> line 23.</p>
<p>Now, what if we knew that <em>sometimes</em>, for some reason, an exception like this might
be thrown when we call <code>fetchAllShipsData()</code>. And when that happens, we <em>don't</em> want
to kill the page or show an error. Instead, we want to - temporarily - render the
page with zero ships.</p>
<p>How can we do this? First, surround the line - or lines - that might fail with a
try-catch block. In the <code>catch</code>, add <code>\Exception $e</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="8c4ace315b">
    <div class="meta">
        <div class="actions">
